{"title_page": "Terenci Moix", "text_new": "{{cleanup|reason=references are a mess and information generally needs to be more organised|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer \n| name = Terenci Moix\n| image = Terenci Moix.jpg\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1942|01|05|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Spain\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2003|04|02|1942|01|05|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Spain\n| occupation = [[writer]], [[novelist]]\n| language = Spanish, [[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n| nationality = Spanish\n| period =\n| genre =\n| subject =\n| movement =\n| notableworks = \n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| awards = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ramon Llull Novel Award]] (1986)\n* [[Fernando Lara Novel Award]] (1989)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Terenci Moix''' ({{IPA-ca|t\u0259\u02c8\u027e\u025bnsi \u02c8mo\u0283}}; real name '''Ramon Moix i Meseguer'''; 5 January 1942, in [[Barcelona]] &ndash; 2 April 2003, in Barcelona) was a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] writer, who wrote in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and in [[Catalan language|Catalan]]. He is also the brother of poet/novelist [[Ana Maria Moix]].\n\n==Life and work==\nHe had a self-taught education. His first work, ''[[La torre de los vicios capitales]]'' (''La torre dels vicis capitals,'' in catalan), was published in 1968. Many of his early works criticised the values of his time, especially the official morality of [[Francoism]]. In 1990, he wrote and published a children's book called, ''Los Grandes Mitos del Cine'' (English version as \"The Greatest Stories of Hollywood Cinema\"), which is illustrated by [[Willi Glasauer]], and published by [[C\u00edrculo de Lectores]]. This children's book includes fun facts, trivia, and information accompanied by photos and [[Willi Glasauer]]'s illustrations of the classic Hollywood films and stars such as ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'', ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'', ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'', and ''[[Tarzan the Ape Man (1932 film)|Tarzan the Ape Man]]''.<ref>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/almanaque-cultural-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x46374571<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/calendario-almanaque-circulo-lectores-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x38744187<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/almanaque-calendario-1990-circulo-lectores-grandes-mitos-cine-ver-fotos~x48404353<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/calendario-almanaque-circulo-lectores-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x47612692<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/coleccionismo-revistas-periodicos/almanaque-o-calendario-cultural-1990-portada-rita-hayworth~x46159748<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/almanaque-cultural-1990~x36992965<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/cine-revistas/almanaque-cultural-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x25320070<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/almanaque-cultural-circulo-lectores-1990-mitos-cine-textos-terenci-moix-charlot-superman~x51434952<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/coleccionismo/dibujos-willi-glasauer-para-almanaque-blanco-negro-ano-1994~x30216850<br>http://www.milanuncios.com/comics/3-almanaques-culturales-circulo-lectores-71682103.htm<br>http://www.milanuncios.com/calendarios-de-coleccion/3-almanaque-cultural-1989-1990-1991-194631111.htm<br>http://www.milanuncios.com/calendarios-de-coleccion/almanaque-1990-grandes-mitos-del-cine-152055322.htm<br>http://www.ebay.es/itm/1990-ALMANAQUE-CULTURAL-Grandes-Mitos-del-Cine-por-Terenci-Moix-Rita-Hayworth-/361652661879?hash=item54342dae77:g:knsAAOSwsTxXj3A3<br>https://es.wallapop.com/item/calendario-cultural-ano-1990-121848800</ref>\n\nOther works explored [[camp aesthetics]], an element of his work studied by [[Timothy M. McGovern]]. He wrote in several newspapers: [[Tele-Expr\u00e9s]], [[Tele-Estel]], [[El Correo Catal\u00e1n]], ''[[Destino (magazine)|Destino]]'', [[Nuevos Fotogramas]], [[Serra d'Or]], and [[El Pa\u00eds]]. He was openly [[homosexual]], and participated in many TV gatherings. He died of [[emphysema|lung emphysema]], which is related to his use of [[tobacco]].\n\nIn 1992 he won the [[Ramon Llull Novel Award]] for ''El sexe dels \u00e0ngels''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1992/04/23/cultura/703980010_850215.html |title=Terenci Moix gana el Premio Ram\u00f3n Llull con 'El sexe dels \u00e0ngels' |first=Xavier |last=Moret |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Barcelona |language=Spanish |date=23 April 1992 |access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref> In 1996 he became the first winner of the [[Fernando Lara Novel Award]] for his then-unpublished work ''El amargo don de la belleza''.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5WUnAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Terenci+Moix%22+%22Premio+Fernando+Lara%22 |title=Tod@ la historia homo: Hacia la normalizaci\u00f3n [1993\u20131997] |first1=Francesc |last1=Navarro i Ferr\u00e9 |first2=Paco |last2=Alcaide |publisher=Baupr\u00e9s Ediciones |isbn=9788434568334 |page=24 |language=Spanish |year=1999 |access-date=5 September 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAn annual [[literature prize]], bearing his name, the [[Terenci Moix Fundaci\u00f3n Arena de Narrativa Gay y L\u00e9sbica]], has been instituted; won most recently by the Anglo-Spanish novelist [[Rafael Pe\u00f1as Cruz]] for his coming-of-age work, ''Charlie''.\n\n==Novels==\n*''[[La torre de los vicios capitales]]''\n*''[[El dia que murio Marilyn]]''\n*''[[Olas sobre una roca desierta]]''\n*''[[M\u00f3n mascle]]''\n*''[[La caiguda de L'imperi sodomita]]''\n*''[[La increada conciencia de la raza o melodrama]]''\n*''[[Sadistic, esperpentic i adhuc metafisic]]''\n*''[[Nuestro Virgen de los m\u00e1rtires]]''\n*''[[Amami, Alfredo! o polvo de estrellas]]''\n*''[[No digas que fue un sue\u00f1o]]''\n*''[[Garras de astracan]]''\n*''[[Mujercisimas]]''\n*''[[La herida de la esfinge]]''\n*''[[El arpista ciego]]''\n*''El amargo don de la belleza'' (2011), {{ISBN|84-08-01899-X}}\n\n==Collections of short stories==\n*''[[La torre de los vicios capitals]]''\n*''[[Tots els contes]]'' (''[[Todos los cuentos]]'')\n\n==Essays==\n*''[[Iniciaci\u00f3 a una hist\u00f2ria del cine]]''\n*''[[Los c\u00f3mics, arte para el consumo y formas pop]]''\n*''[[El sadismo de nuestra infancia]]''\n*''[[Terenci del Nilo]]''\n*''[[Cr\u00f3nicas italianas]]''\n*''[[Hollywood stories]]'' (2 vols.)\n*''[[Los Grandes Mitos del Cine|The Greatest Stories of Hollywood Cinema]]'' (Illustrated by [[Willi Glasauer]]), ([[C\u00edrculo de Lectores]])\n*''[[Tres viajes rom\u00e1nticos]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://www.tablondeanuncios.com/colecciones/terence_moix_la_noche_no_es_hermosa-3299412.htm\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.escriptors.cat/autors/moixt/pagina.php?id_sec=3824 Terenci Moix] at the Association of Catalan Language Writers, AELC. In Catalan, English and Spanish.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moix, Terenci}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Deaths from emphysema]]\n[[Category:Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:Spanish male novelists]]\n[[Category:Spanish essayists]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language LGBT writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|reason=references are a mess and information generally needs to be more organised|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer \n| name = Terenci Moix\n| image = Terenci Moix.jpg\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1942|01|05|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Spain\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2003|04|02|1942|01|05|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Spain\n| occupation = [[writer]], [[novelist]]\n| language = Spanish, [[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n| nationality = Spanish\n| period =\n| genre =\n| subject =\n| movement =\n| notableworks = \n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| awards = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ramon Llull Novel Award]] (1986)\n* [[Fernando Lara Novel Award]] (1989)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Terenci Moix''' ({{IPA-ca|t\u0259\u02c8\u027e\u025bnsi \u02c8mo\u0283}}; real name '''Ramon Moix i Meseguer'''; 5 January 1942, in [[Barcelona]] &ndash; 2 April 2003, in Barcelona) was a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] writer, who wrote in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and in [[Catalan language|Catalan]]. He is also the brother of poet/novelist [[Ana Maria Moix]].\n\n==Life and work==\nHe had a self-taught education. His first work, ''[[La torre de los vicios capitales]]'' (''La torre dels vicis capitals,'' in catalan), was published in 1968. Many of his early works criticised the values of his time, especially the official morality of [[Francoism]]. In 1990, he wrote and published a children's book called, ''Los Grandes Mitos del Cine'' (English version as \"The Greatest Stories of Hollywood Cinema\"), which is illustrated by [[Willi Glasauer]], and published by [[C\u00edrculo de Lectores]]. This children's book includes fun facts, trivia, and information accompanied by photos and [[Willi Glasauer]]'s illustrations of the classic Hollywood films and stars such as ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'', ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'', ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'', and ''[[Tarzan the Ape Man (1932 film)|Tarzan the Ape Man]]''.<ref>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/almanaque-cultural-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x46374571<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/calendario-almanaque-circulo-lectores-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x38744187<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/almanaque-calendario-1990-circulo-lectores-grandes-mitos-cine-ver-fotos~x48404353<br>http://www.todocoleccion.net/calendarios-antiguos/calendario-almanaque-circulo-lectores-1990-grandes-mitos-cine~x47612692<br>http://www.todocoleccion.n